  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has developed progressively over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a criminal concept in the 1930s, initially targeting organized crime's financial activities\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like gambling and bootlegging\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (US) first introduced reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act in the United States criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international anti-money laundering standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- 1990 Council of Europe Convention introduced broader international legal frameworks\n- Gradual expansion of regulations to cover terrorist financing after 9/11\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approaches:\n- Comprehensive Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n- Increasingly sophisticated technological tracking mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Expanding regulations to address cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n- Growing focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Increased global coordination of enforcement efforts\n\nThis progression reflects evolving strategies to combat financial crimes.",
